15 Jan 2009 01:11






The third test is easy: put a D-class in a room, have him open the cookie and hold out the message blindfolded, remove the message without anyone seeing it, kill the D-class, then read it. (It won't predict things which happen after their death, presumably.)

The first test is trickier, but not impossible. Here's a rough example, though it needs work: Put a D-class in a situation where he has to guess which number a researcher is thinking - either 1 or 2 - or he dies. Inform him completely of this, then have him open a cookie. The researcher will read the message after the D-class reads it: if it details which number is "correct", then the researcher will think of the other number instead. (A control experiment could be done where the researcher does not see the cookie's predictions.) If an improbable event happens which forces the researcher to choose a number that the cookie predicts, then this SCP is likely capable of probability manipulation.

Damn, I need to think this through a bit more.





